# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler & Toolchain (v5.7 arc)
# TS/JSX lex trio, cx-backend drift + marker, heap reshuffle, aarch64 f64 stubs, distlib + audit + auto-deps gates, lsp globals order, lint/fmt per-file, fn-keyword.
# 15 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "ts_lex_jsx_lookahead_is_arrow_jsx_terminators"
description = "TS_LOOKAHEAD_IS_ARROW's COLON-branch must treat JSX closing tokens as scope terminators or it false-positives on unrelated arrows far past the expression"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts", "lex", "jsx", "lookahead", "v5.7.6"]
content = """
Filed: v5.7.6 P4.3d (the bug that rolled back v5.7.5 P4.3d-2).

When TS_LOOKAHEAD_IS_ARROW determines whether `(` starts an arrow
function, it scans for the matching `)`, then checks what follows.
If COLON, it enters a secondary scan for `=>` (return-type form
`(args): T => body`).

The COLON-branch's secondary scan tracked LPAREN/RPAREN/LBRACKET/
RBRACKET/LT/GT for depth, and treated LBRACE/SEMI/COMMA at depth==0
as terminators. JSX tokens were SKIPPED — none of them affected
depth, none terminated.

For ternary `a ? (<JSX/>) : (<JSX2/>)` followed by REAL JSX text +
much later an arrow function in the same source: the COLON-branch
scanned past the else-branch's RPAREN (depth → 0), past JSX
closing tokens (JSX_EXPR_CLOSE, JSX_CLOSE_END, etc. — all skipped),
into adjacent code, and FOUND an unrelated `=>` at depth==0.
LOOKAHEAD returned 1 (arrow), parser entered ARROW_PAREN, then
ARROW_PARAMS errored on the JSX_OPEN_START at the start of
`(<JSX/>)`.

Fix: COLON-branch treats JSX_EXPR_CLOSE / JSX_CLOSE_END /
JSX_FRAGMENT_CLOSE / JSX_SELF_CLOSE / JSX_OPEN_END as terminators
at depth==0. A closed-out JSX construct can't be inside an arrow
return-type position, so `=>` past it is unrelated.

Why this resisted bisect at v5.7.5 P4.3d-2: the bug requires (1) a
ternary with JSX-containing parens, (2) an unrelated arrow function
SOMEWHERE later in the same source. Single-line removal can't isolate
because it depends on TWO non-adjacent constructs. Removing either
makes the test pass; the bug only manifests in their combination.

The disambig change matters: same fix may apply to other lookahead
heuristics that walk past JSX without recognizing scope.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ts_lex_jsx_disambig_byteskip_only"
description = "Pre-flight BYTE_SKIP balance check is sufficient JSX-vs-generic-arrow disambiguation; the v5.7.3 post-> ( heuristic false-positives on JSX text starting with ("
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts", "lex", "jsx", "disambig", "v5.7.6"]
content = """
Filed: v5.7.6 P4.3d.

v5.7.3 introduced a heuristic for `<` in expression context:
scan ahead to matching `>` at depth 0; if next char is `(`,
bail (it's a generic arrow `<T>(args)`). Otherwise proceed
as JSX.

This false-positives on real JSX where the open tag's text
content starts with `(`, like `<span>(optional)</span>`.
Lex bails on `<span>`, falls through to LT operator, then
`/` of `</span>` becomes regex, then unterminated regex
error (code 11).

Fix v5.7.6: removed the post-`>` `(` heuristic entirely.
Pre-flight BYTE_SKIP balance check (already present in
v5.7.5) does the right thing for both cases:
- Real JSX: BYTE_SKIP finds matching close tag, succeeds.
- Generic arrow `<T>(args) => body`: BYTE_SKIP never finds
  `</T>` close (generic types have no closing tag); walks
  to EOF; returns start (bail).

Lesson: a heuristic that returns false based on adjacent
characters is fragile. A semantic check (does this construct
balance?) is more robust and serves as the disambiguator
naturally.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "ts_lex_jsx_mode_stack_design"
description = "JSX lexing uses the existing template-stack with mode values 4=JSX_TAG, 5=JSX_TEXT, 8=JSX_EXPR — main TS_LEX loop dispatches per-mode"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["ts", "lex", "jsx", "modes", "v5.7.6"]
content = """
Filed: v5.7.6 P4.3d.

JSX lexing in v5.7.6 reuses the existing template-literal
mode stack (TS_TEMPLATE_STACK_OFF) by adding three new
mode values:

- 4 = JSX_TAG_MODE: inside `<TAG ...>` open or `</TAG>`
  close, expecting attrs or close-of-tag. Dispatched
  to TS_LEX_JSX_TAG.
- 5 = JSX_TEXT_MODE: between tags, expecting children
  (text, JSX expr, nested elements). Dispatched to
  TS_LEX_JSX_TEXT.
- 8 = JSX_EXPR_MODE: inside `{...}` of JSX expr. Main
  TS_LEX loop runs normal expression tokenization;
  matching `}` (handled in `}` operator) pops mode 8
  + emits JSX_EXPR_CLOSE.

Existing values: 0/1 = template body, 2 = `${...}`
template-interp, 3 = nested brace marker (reused for
nesting inside both 2 and 8).

Why this design works: the main TS_LEX loop's top-of-loop
mode check naturally dispatches to per-mode handlers.
Each call processes ONE structural token + transition;
on next iteration the mode (possibly different) drives
the next dispatch. JSX expression bodies tokenize as
regular TS — no duplication of dispatch logic.

The TS_LEX_JSX entry point pushes mode 4 (or 5 for
fragment) and returns; the walker is GONE — main loop
takes over.

The brace marker (3) reuse means JSX expressions can
contain object literals, function bodies, etc. without
needing separate marker values. The matching-} logic
distinguishes `}` of object literal (top=3 → emit RBRACE)
from `}` of JSX expr (top=8 → emit JSX_EXPR_CLOSE) from
`}` of template interp (top=2 → close interp).
"""


[[entries]]
name = "cx_drift_silent_accumulation_lesson"
description = "main_cx.cyr accumulated 4+ silent drift breakages over v5.6.x + v5.7.x because no CI gate ever built it. v5.7.11 fix + gate."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cx", "drift", "ci-gate", "v5.7.11"]
---
src/main_cx.cyr (the cyrius-x bytecode entry) accumulated
silent drift across many minor releases because no CI gate
built it. Each addition to the shared frontend that x86 and
aarch64 picked up silently broke cx without anyone noticing:

- v5.6.12 added IR_RAW_EMIT to common/ir.cyr; main.cyr +
  main_aarch64.cyr included ir.cyr; main_cx.cyr did not.
  parse_expr.cyr references IR_RAW_EMIT → main_cx.cyr fails
  parse with "undefined variable 'IR_RAW_EMIT'".
- v5.6.x optimization arc added _AARCH64_BACKEND /
  _flags_reflect_rax / _last_push_cp / _last_emovca_cp /
  _last_movca_popr_cp / _INLINE_OK / _LOOPVAR_OK globals to
  x86 + aarch64 emit. Never added to cx emit. parse_*.cyr
  references all of them.
- v5.5.x platform completion added _TARGET_MACHO /
  _TARGET_PE to x86 + aarch64 emit. Same pattern.
- main_cx.cyr's brk extension was 0x54A000 (5.5 MB) — never
  reached the tok_types region at S+0x74A000 (7.5 MB). cc5_cx
  SIGSEGV'd at LEX the moment a non-empty input landed any
  token. Probably broken since whatever earlier reshuffle
  put tok_types at 0x74A000.

Each surfaced one at a time as v5.7.11 plowed through; each
fix revealed the next missing piece.

The PERMANENT FIX is the CI gate, not the per-piece adds.
tests/regression-cx-build.sh (scripts/check.sh gate 4u)
verifies cc5 builds main_cx.cyr cleanly + cc5_cx starts
clean on empty/trivial input. Drift cannot recur silently —
any future shared-frontend addition that breaks cx fails
check.sh immediately.

Lesson for new backends (RISC-V at v5.7.13): add the CI
gate the moment the backend builds. Don't wait for "real
testing" — drift accumulates in the gap between "compiles"
and "runs through full test suite". A 5-line gate that
verifies build-only is enough to catch 90% of drift; the
remaining 10% surfaces when the runtime gates are added.

Sister memory: feedback_dont_assume_unmaintained.md (don't
pitch retiring drifted subsystems; fix them).


[[entries]]
name = "target_cx_backend_marker_path_b"
description = "v5.7.12 _TARGET_CX backend marker for path-B guards on direct x86-byte emits in shared frontend codepaths."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cx", "backend-marker", "path-b", "v5.7.12"]
---
parse_*.cyr (the shared frontend) emits raw x86 instruction
bytes via EB(S, 0xNN) / E2(S, 0xNNNN) / E3(S, 0xNNNNNN)
calls in many code paths. On x86 and aarch64 builds those
calls produce native or arch-specific bytes (aarch64 uses
arch-conditional branches). On cx the same calls write x86
bytes into the CYX bytecode stream — corrupting the output.

v5.7.12 ships path B: a `_TARGET_CX` flag (=1 only when
backend/cx/emit.cyr is the active include; =0 in x86 +
aarch64 emit) gates direct-x86-emit sites. Pattern:

  if (_TARGET_CX == 0) {
      EB(S, 0x48); EB(S, 0x8D); EB(S, 0x05);  // x86 LEA
  }

7 sites guarded in v5.7.12 (per
docs/audit/2026-04-27-cx-direct-emit-inventory.md):
parse_decl.cyr struct field load; parse_expr.cyr PIC fn-addr,
&local x86 LEA, PIC closure-literal addr, f64 cmp x86 SETcc
chain; parse_fn.cyr struct-return rep movsb, regalloc
save/restore.

The high-volume offender was regalloc save/restore — every
fn with `_cur_fn_regalloc > 0` (which is most of them post-
v5.6.24 default-on regalloc) leaked `48 89 5d f8 4c 89 65 f0`
etc. callee-save chains into the cx bytecode stream. Path-B
guard wrap on the 5-line save and 5-line restore blocks
removed the bulk of the noise.

Path B is the TACTICAL fix; path A (replace direct emits
with named abstract ops in each backend) is pinned long-term
in the roadmap. Path A becomes the right move when RISC-V
(v5.7.13) makes the guard pattern unwieldy or 2+ new direct-
emit sites slip past static analysis.

Pre-existing unfixed: cx codegen literal-arg propagation
bug (syscall(60, 42) bytecode emits `movi r0, 0` instead of
`movi r0, 60` / `movi r0, 42`). Pinned as a v5.7.x patch
slot — not a v5.7.12 regression.


[[entries]]
name = "heap_reshuffle_pattern_v5_7_10"
description = "v5.7.10 input_buf 512KB → 1MB via +0x100000 shift of 95 distinct heap-region addresses. Disambiguation discipline."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "reshuffle", "input_buf", "v5.7.10"]
---
v5.7.10 widened input_buf 524 288 B → 1 048 576 B because
hisab/dist/hisab.cyr was at 96% of the cap (505,237 B) and
actively censoring upstream to fit; every consumer of hisab
inherited the full 505 KB via cyrius's [deps] auto-prepend,
leaving 19 KB of budget for its own source.

The cap-value bump itself was 18 sites (3 per main_*.cyr
file × 6 files) plus 1 PP IFDEF copy-back cap in lex_pp.cyr.
The HARD work was the heap reshuffle: input_buf at 0..0x80000
was packed back-to-back with compiler-state regions starting
at 0x8C100. Widening input_buf to 0..0x100000 collided with
all of them.

**95 distinct heap-region addresses** in 0x80000..0xFFFFF
shifted +0x100000 to land in 0x180000..0x1FFFFF. **NOT
+0x80000** — the naive shift would have collided with 3
existing 6-digit squatters (fn_deprecated_msg at 0x104000,
FNV-1a fn-name hash at 0x10C000, vname_offsets at 0x11A000,
brk arg at 0x122000, vsize at 0x12A000, vtype at 0x13A000,
output_buf at 0x14A000). +0x100000 lifts cleanly into the
empty 0x180000..0x1FFFFF range. Verified via comm -12 on
predicted-shifted vs existing-addresses pre-shift = zero
collisions.

brk extension UNCHANGED at 0x348C000 (52.5 MB) — the
shifted regions pack into already-allocated heap. v5.7.7's
fixup-cap-1M brk was already large enough.

Sed sweep: regenerated by awk from the address list (95
distinct), applied via `find src -name '*.cyr' -exec sed -i
-f /tmp/shift.sed {} +`. Bare-hex comment refs (96 of them)
shifted in a separate pass; 4 boundary-comment over-shifts
hand-corrected (where 0x80000 was the input_buf END, not a
region address — should have stayed 0x80000 for tok_names
range or become 0x100000 for new input_buf end).

Lesson for the next reshuffle (input_buf 1MB → 2MB if
hisab-class folds compound further):
- ALWAYS run the comm collision check between predicted
  shifted addresses and existing addresses pre-shift.
- Bare-hex sweeps over-shift boundary comments — manually
  verify any "X ends at 0xN" / "regions below 0xN" comments
  after the sed pass.
- brk extension is a separate decision from the shift delta.
  Don't bump brk unless the new region layout actually
  overflows the allocation.

Reference cap-bump trajectory: input_buf 256 KB → 512 KB
(v3.6.7) → 1 MB (v5.7.10). Sister memory:
feedback_cap_bumps_recurring.md.

[[entries]]
name = "forked_helper_offset_typo_cx_backend_v5_7_23"
description = "v5.7.23 cx codegen literal-arg propagation bug — TOKVAL read from wrong heap region"
category = "cyrius"
---
v5.7.23 (2026-04-27) — single-character typo fix in
`src/backend/cx/emit.cyr`'s `TOKVAL` helper. Backend-fork
hazard pattern: when a backend module forks shared frontend
helpers, every offset literal is a candidate for typo.

The bug: `TOKVAL` in cx backend read tokens from
`S + 0x94A000 + i*8` instead of the canonical
`S + 0xB4A000 + i*8` write site in `src/frontend/lex.cyr:99`.
0x94A000 is a zero-initialized gap region between
`tok_types` (0x74A000) and `tok_values` (0xB4A000) in the
heap map; PEEKV(S) therefore always returned 0 in cc5_cx.

Surface: `syscall(60, 42)` emitted `MOVI r0, 0` for both
args, plus a spurious `warning: syscall arity mismatch`
on stderr (because `sc_num` got read as 0 = SYS_READ
arity 3, not 60 = SYS_EXIT arity 1; the parser's argc==0
branch reads `sc_num = _cfv` and `_cfv` was 0). The
implicit-exit syscall's `60` literal propagated correctly
because main_cx's epilogue synthesizes the exit syscall
through a hard-coded path rather than the lex token
table.

Origin: introduced at v5.7.12 path-B work when the cx
backend module forked `TOKTYP`/`TOKVAL`/`PEEKV` from the
x86 emit module. `TOKTYP`'s `0x74A000` was copied
correctly; `TOKVAL`'s `0xB4A000` was hand-typed and
fat-fingered to `0x94A000`. The v5.7.12
`regression-cx-roundtrip.sh` gate explicitly noted
"Exit-code propagation through `syscall(60, X)`" as out
of scope, slotting the audit as future work — v5.7.23
closed it.

The fix is one character: 0x94A000 → 0xB4A000.

Audit pattern for similar forked-helper bugs:
```
grep -rn "0x[0-9A-F]\{6\}A000" src/backend/
```
Diff each region's reads/writes against the canonical
write sites in `src/frontend/lex.cyr` +
`src/frontend/parse_*.cyr`. A 30-second numerical
cross-check at fork time would have caught this.

Detection method that worked: instrument the suspect
emit fn to print the value it receives. CX_MOVI showed
val=0 for the user syscall args but val=60 for the
implicit exit — the asymmetry pointed at the parser-side
read path, not the emit path. Then `grep -rn "fn TOKVAL"
src/` produced 4 hits across backends; the offset
divergence between cx (0x94A000) and x86/aarch64
(0xB4A000) was immediately visible.

Lesson: when a fork is mostly a copy-paste of a small
table of magic numbers (heap offsets, opcode tables, cap
constants), invest 30 seconds in a `diff -y` between fork
and origin BEFORE shipping. The cost of finding the
typo via downstream surfacing is days; the cost of
finding it via cross-check is seconds.


[[entries]]
name = "verify_slot_premise_aarch64_f64_stubs_v5_7_30"
description = "aarch64 f64 basic-op stubs returned 0 for years before v5.7.30 surfaced them via premise verification on a polyfill task"
category = "cyrius"
subcategory = "field_notes_compiler"
---
v5.7.30 was originally pinned as "aarch64 f64_exp polyfill" — a
narrow targeted addition. **Premise verification before
implementation** uncovered a much bigger bug: every f64 basic
op on aarch64 was already broken. `EMIT_F64_BINOP` and 6 sibling
emits in `src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr` were stubs (`return 0;`).
`f64_add(1.0, 2.0)` returned 2.0 (the second arg, since the
parser left it in x0 and EMIT_F64_BINOP emitted nothing), with
stack leak from the unpopped first arg. Probably broken since
v5.4.x when aarch64 cross-build first shipped.

The user-direction at v5.7.30 entry: split into two slots.
v5.7.30 ships basic ops; v5.7.31 ships polyfills using working
basic ops. Both shipped same day (2026-04-28).

**Lesson**: verify slot premise before implementing. The
roadmap framing ("polyfill") implied basic ops already worked.
A 5-minute test (`assert f64_add(2.0, 3.0) == 5.0` cross-built
to aarch64, run on the Pi) would have caught this years
earlier. Pinned method: any aarch64-targeted slot starts with
"run a basic-op smoke test on the Pi" before designing.

This is the same shape as v5.7.34's catch — v5.7.27 raised
x86 codebuf 1MB→3MB but DIDN'T raise aarch64's matching cap
in `src/backend/aarch64/emit.cyr` `EB()`. Backend parity
checks are routinely missed because the tests live one
ssh hop away.

[[entries]]
name = "audit_silent_skip_is_false_green_v5_7_36"
description = "scripts/check.sh's silent-skip on missing fmt/lint binaries reported false-PASS; same shape as v5.7.29 set -e abort masking"
category = "cyrius"
subcategory = "field_notes_compiler"
---
Pre-v5.7.36 `scripts/check.sh` resolved `CYRFMT` /
`CYRLINT` only as `$ROOT/build/cyrfmt` / `cyrlint`. On a
fresh checkout (only `build/cc3` + `build/cc5` committed),
those paths don't exist; the audit emitted `skip: cyrfmt
not built` / `skip: cyrlint not built` and counted nothing
toward pass/fail. A green "52/52 PASS" report on a build
that hadn't actually formatted or linted anything.

Surfaced when the user re-set up the toolchain on a fresh
Arch install and ran `sh scripts/check.sh` against an
already-installed-via-tarball toolchain. The installed
binaries lived at `~/.cyrius/bin/cyrfmt` / `cyrlint` but
check.sh's resolution didn't try PATH, so both gates
silently skipped.

v5.7.36 fix:
1. `CYRFMT` / `CYRLINT` resolution falls back to
   `command -v <tool>` if the in-repo build/ path is empty.
2. The `skip: not built` branch became
   `check "format/lint (stdlib)" "1"` — a real FAIL with a
   message pointing at `cyrius lsp` / `cyriusly setup` /
   manual build instructions.

**Lesson**: silent skips in audit gates are equivalent to
v5.7.29's `set -e` + `tail` masking — the failure mode is
"green report but the test never ran." Any new gate added
to check.sh should FAIL-loud when its prerequisite tooling
is absent, not skip. Pinned method: fresh-install
rehearsal once per minor (last: never; first: v5.7.36)
catches this class because a fresh checkout exposes the
"binary not built yet" path.

[[entries]]
name = "distlib_per_module_read_cap_v5_7_36"
description = "cyrius distlib's per-module read buffer was 65535 bytes; modules > 64 KB silently truncated mid-bundle"
category = "cyrius"
subcategory = "field_notes_compiler"
---
`cmd_distlib` in `cbt/commands.cyr` allocates a per-module
read buffer to slurp each source file into memory before
writing to the bundle. Pre-v5.7.36 size: `alloc(65536)` /
`file_read_all(..., 65535)`. Source files larger than 64
KB had their tail bytes truncated silently — no error, no
warning, the bundle file just ended early.

Mabda hit it generating its dist after hardware-iter accretion
pushed at least one module past 64 KB. Bumped to 262144 (256
KB) at v5.7.36 — three quarters of breathing room on top of
mabda's current need.

`tests/regression-distlib-large-module.sh` (gate 4ar)
synthesises a ~78 KB module with a sentinel on the last
line, runs `cyrius distlib`, asserts the bundle contains
the sentinel. Pre-v5.7.36 the test fails (sentinel
truncated); post-v5.7.36 passes.

**Lesson**: per-module read buffers in `cbt/commands.cyr`
need explicit caps that scale with consumer growth. The
fixup table cap pattern (16K → 32K → 262K → 1M across
v5.x) is the precedent — bump the static cap until a
fourth bump, then convert to a dynamic vec. The first
bump is fine; the third is the warning sign.

[[entries]]
name = "auto_deps_gate_inflates_self_host_size_v5_7_38"
description = "Adding `cyrius soak` to the auto-deps gate caused cmd_soak's compile() of src/main.cyr to prepend all manifest deps and blow the 2MB expanded-source cap"
category = "cyrius"
subcategory = "field_notes_compiler"
---
v5.7.38 added `.scyr` (soak) + `.smcyr` (smoke) discovery to
`cmd_soak` / `cmd_smoke`. Adding both verbs to the auto-deps
gate (cbt/cyrius.cyr line 122) caused the built-in self-host
loop inside `cmd_soak` to fail with:

```
[1/1] error: expanded source exceeds 2MB (2317668 bytes) in PP_IFDEF_PASS iter=0
=== soak complete: 0/1 passed, 1 failed ===
```

Root cause: `cmd_soak`'s built-in loop calls
`compile("src/main.cyr", cc5_t)`. With auto-deps active,
`_dep_includes` is populated with the cyrius project's six
manifest deps (sigil/sakshi/patra/yukti/mabda/sankoch). The
six dep bundles get prepended to src/main.cyr's 7,400-LOC
compiler source → expanded source crosses the 2 MB
preprocessor cap → fail.

Fix: `_skip_deps = 1` save/restore around the built-in loop.
The `.scyr` walker (after) restores `_skip_deps` so user
harnesses get the same auto-prepend as `.tcyr`/`.bcyr`/
`.fcyr` (per the v5.7.21 fuzz parity slot).

```cyr
fn cmd_soak(iters) {
    var saved_skip_deps = _skip_deps;
    _skip_deps = 1;       # built-in loop compiles src/main.cyr — no auto-prepend
    ...iterations + .tcyr suite...
    _skip_deps = saved_skip_deps;
    ...walk .scyr files (auto-prepend OK here)...
}
```

**Lesson**: auto-deps gate is a coarse on/off per command.
Any `cmd_*` that calls `compile()` against sources near
the 2 MB cap (i.e. compiling cyrius itself, or any
multi-thousand-LOC consumer entry point) needs `_skip_deps`
guarding around those specific calls. The cap raise from 1
MB → 2 MB landed at v5.6.40; another bump to 4 MB or beyond
should be considered if a third command hits this shape
(third = cap exhaustion signal per the
`heap_cap_growth_pattern` entry above).

[[entries]]
name = "lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions_v5_7_39"
description = "cyrius requires top-level `var X` to be declared before any fn body that references X — applies to programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr's symbol-table backing buffers too"
category = "cyrius"
subcategory = "field_notes_compiler"
---
v5.7.39 added a symbol indexer to programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr
with parallel-array globals (`_sym_name_off`, `_sym_path_off`,
etc., backing buffers `_sym_names_buf`, `_sym_paths_buf`,
`_lsp_indexed_buf`). All declared at top-level BEFORE the
fn definitions that reference them, then allocated inside
`lsp_index_init()` called from `main()` after `alloc_init()`.

This works because cyrius parses the file in source order:
when the parser hits `fn handle_definition() { ... uses
_sym_name_off ... }`, the global var slot has already been
declared (at top level above the fn). The runtime initialization
(via `alloc()` in main()) happens later — fn bodies don't run
until called.

If the globals were declared BELOW the fn definitions,
compile would fail with `undefined variable '_sym_name_off'`.
Same forward-ref-init class as v5.7.32 cyrlint warns about
for `var X = expr_using_Y` shapes — but that's compile-time
parse order, this is global-decl-before-fn-body order.

**Lesson**: when adding a substantial program (cyrlint,
cyrius-lsp, programs/api_surface.cyr) with state shared
across multiple fns, declare ALL state globals as a single
block at the top of the file (after stdlib includes,
before any fn). Init via a fn called from main(), not
inline at the global decl. This avoids both:
- forward-ref-init errors (v5.7.32 cyrlint shape)
- `undefined variable` parse errors (fn body referencing
  a global declared later)

The pattern is mechanical; the bug surfaces every time
state is added incrementally and a global is "where the
fn that uses it lives." Centralize.

[[entries]]
name = "distlib_64kb_truncation_v5736"
description = "cyrius distlib silently truncated modules >64 KB pre-5.7.36 — mabda's backend_native.cyr surfaced it"
category = "cyrius"
---
Pre-5.7.36 (`cbt/commands.cyr` Step 6.5(b) era), `cyrius distlib`
read each `[lib].modules` source file into a fixed 64-KB buffer:

```cyrius
var fbuf = alloc(65536);
var flen = file_read_all(mod_path, fbuf, 65535);
```

Files larger than 65535 bytes had their tail silently dropped from
the bundled `dist/<pkg>.cyr`. No warning, no error, no diagnostic.
The bundle still compiled — it just had every `fn` defined past
byte 65535 quietly missing. Consumers pulling `[deps.<pkg>]` would
hit unresolved-symbol link failures.

**Trigger case:** mabda's `src/backend_native.cyr` grew past 64 KB
during the Phase C (texture + render) work. `backend_native_new`,
the `native_texture_*` family, and `native_rt_*` family — all
defined past line 1500 — vanished from `dist/mabda.cyr`. The
truncation only surfaced when a regenerate-and-link sweep on a
fresh dev box (post-Arch reinstall) tried to use the regenerated
bundle.

**Fixed upstream in cyrius 5.7.36** (commit `8c75f3f`,
`repairs to installer and check.sh` — bumps the per-module read
buffer 64 KB → 256 KB and the `file_read_all` cap to 262143). The
comment in `cbt/commands.cyr` after the fix explicitly credits
mabda for surfacing the wall:

> v5.7.36: per-module read buffer raised 64KB → 256KB. mabda
> surfaced the wall when its dist generation truncated at the
> 65535-byte read cap (single-module sources outgrew 64KB after
> hardware-iter accretion). 256KB is the next breathing room
> without committing to a dynamic vec — revisit if a module ever
> crosses 192KB.

**Lessons that generalize:**

1. Fixed-cap byte buffers in toolchain code are a recurring class —
   `stale_fixed_cap_pattern` (this file) covered prior instances
   (cc3 stdin truncation, etc.). The read-buffer-as-source-of-
   silent-truncation shape is the same. Worth a sweep across cyrius
   for `alloc(<small_const>)` patterns where the data is
   user-controlled.
2. **Diagnostic, even if hard-fail isn't appropriate.** A
   `warning: module X exceeds N-byte read buffer; output may be
   truncated` would have made this a 5-minute fix instead of a
   what-symbol-is-missing investigation. File-IO with implicit caps
   should always emit a "you hit the cap" diagnostic when the read
   matches the buffer size exactly (high-confidence truncation
   indicator).
3. **Bundle gates as CI.** Mabda's CI runs `cyrius distlib` and
   diff-checks `dist/<pkg>.cyr`. The diff would catch ANY drift,
   including silent truncation — but only if the project actually
   re-runs distlib after every source bump. The session 26 surface
   happened because the pre-existing committed `dist/mabda.cyr` was
   built BEFORE backend_native.cyr crossed 64 KB; the truncation
   was latent until regen.

The 256-KB cap is breathing room, not a permanent answer. If any
future module crosses 192 KB, revisit the cap or move to a
dynamic-grow buffer (vec-style; cyrius stdlib has the primitive).

[[entries]]
name = "lint_fmt_per_file_in_5_7"
description = "cyrius lint and cyrius fmt --check became per-file in 5.7.x — the bare repo-wide invocation is gone"
category = "cyrius"
---
In Cyrius 5.7.x the `lint` and `fmt --check` subcommands take a
single file argument and require it; the bare repo-wide invocation
documented in older project CLAUDE.mds (e.g. mabda pre-2026-04-30)
errors with `Usage: cyrius lint <file.cyr>`.

```sh
# Pre-5.7.x (no longer works):
cyrius lint
cyrius fmt --check

# 5.7.x (current):
cyrius lint src/foo.cyr
cyrius fmt src/foo.cyr --check
```

**Project-wide form is now `cyrius audit`** — wraps a `check.sh`
that runs the cyrius compiler's own self-host + regression suite.
**Two caveats** caught when bringing up mabda on a fresh Arch box
post-reinstall (2026-04-30):

1. `install.sh` did not copy `scripts/check.sh` into `~/.cyrius/bin/`
   pre-5.7.36. `cyrius audit` errored with
   `/home/.../check.sh: No such file or directory`. Fixed in 5.7.36
   via the `repairs to installer and check.sh` commit; before then,
   the workaround was to copy the script manually.
2. Even when `check.sh` is installed, it runs the cyrius compiler's
   OWN self-host audit (LLVM regression tests, target-specific
   bring-up gates). For DOWNSTREAM consumer projects (mabda, soorat,
   etc.), this is the wrong gate — it tests cyrius, not the
   consumer's surface.

**Right-shape for downstream consumer CI/local sweeps:** a shell
loop over the project's source tree.

```sh
for f in src/*.cyr; do cyrius lint "$f" || exit 1; done
for f in src/*.cyr; do cyrius fmt "$f" --check >/dev/null || exit 1; done
```

This is what mabda CI uses post-5.7.30. Worth flagging in any
project's CLAUDE.md / CI workflow that still describes the bare
form — the toolchain bumped without anyone noticing for a couple of
release cycles.

**Cross-pollination:** the per-file shape may eventually grow into
a `--all` or `--recursive` mode upstream. Until then, the loop is
the contract. Don't write project-side wrappers that assume
otherwise.

[[entries]]
name = "fn_keyword_in_param_position"
description = "v5.7.46: `fn` is reserved keyword and cannot be used as a parameter name even in helper fns; cyrius parser surfaces this with 'expected identifier, got reserved keyword fn' error at the NEXT fn definition, not the offending one"
category = "cyrius"
---
**Discovered at v5.7.46 lib/test.cyr v1 ship.** Tried writing
`fn test_each(cases_vec, fn) { ... fncall1(fn, ...); ... }`
where `fn` was the parameter name (intended to mean "the
callback fn pointer"). The parser rejected with:

```
error:lib/fnptr.cyr:234: expected identifier, got reserved
keyword 'fn' (cannot be used as an identifier; rename the
variable/field/fn)
```

**Note the file path**: error reports at `lib/fnptr.cyr:234`,
which is the NEXT fn definition (`fn fncall5(fp, a, b, c, d, e)`)
the parser encountered after the offending param. The `fn`-as-
parameter-name in `test_each` polluted the parser state somehow,
and `fn fncall5` looked like garbled syntax to the recovery
path.

**Convention** (matches lib/callback.cyr): use `fp` (function
pointer) as the parameter name when you want to receive a fn
pointer. Both `lib/callback.cyr` (v5.0.x) and `lib/test.cyr`
(v5.7.43) follow this — `fn for_each(v, fp)`,
`fn test_each(cases_vec, fp)`.

**Lesson**: cyrius's reserved keywords (fn, var, if, while,
return, etc.) are unconditionally reserved — not just
contextually. Don't shadow them as identifiers anywhere. Error
messages on this can be confusing because the parser may
recover into the next definition before reporting.
